{{Infobox company | name = HortaPharm B.V. | logo = | caption = | type = | traded_as = | genre = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies --> | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = 1990 <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | founder = David Paul Watson | defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | location_city = Amsterdam | location_country = Netherlands <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ist-world.info/OrgUnitDetails.aspx?OrgUnitId=9ccecafe358b4c6891aef7b026d3e6f1# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2012-07-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131005042403/http://www.ist-world.info/OrgUnitDetails.aspx?OrgUnitId=9ccecafe358b4c6891aef7b026d3e6f1# |archive-date=2013-10-05 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref> | locations = | area_served = | key_people = | industry = Horticulture | products = Cannabis based medicine extracts | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | aum = <!-- Only used with financial services companies --> | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = <!-- {{URL|examplesite.com|ExampleSite.com}} --> | footnotes = | intl = }}
'''HortaPharm B.V.''' is a cannabis research and development business in the [[Netherlands]].<ref>[http://www.genetics.org/content/163/1/335.full.pdf+html The Inheritance of Chemical Phenotype in Cannabis sativa L.(HortaPharm B.V., 1075 VS, Amsterdam, The Netherlands)]</ref>
==History== The business was founded by David Paul Watson in 1990. He was soon joined by David W. Pate and eventually Robert C. Clarke. They obtained the first license issued by the Dutch government to permit a ''Cannabis'' research facility in the Netherlands. HortaPharm B.V. has a partnership with [[GW Pharmaceuticals]] to develop ''Cannabis'' varieties for the manufacture of pharmaceuticals.<ref>[http://www.gwpharm.com/23july1998.aspx Details released of collaboration between GW Pharmaceuticals and Hortapharm medicinal cannabis,]</ref>
==Breeding== Using selective breeding and production control, HortaPharm created ''Cannabis'' strains that produce virtually single cannabinoids, approximately 98% [[tetrahydrocannabinol]] or [[cannabidiol]], relative to the total of other cannabinoids present.<ref>{{citation| title=Marijuana and Medicine | url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Marijuana_and_Medicine.html?id=8E3NXew8MIUC | author=Janet E. Joy | author2=Stanley J. Watson Jr. | author3=John A. Benson Jr.|publisher=National Academies Press|year=1999|isbn=9780309071550}}</ref>
