{{Use British English|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Spanish name|'''Bisonó'''|'''Haza'''}}
'''Marcos Rodolfo Bisonó Haza''' is a [[People of the Dominican Republic|Dominican]] businessman and lawyer. Bisonó is currently the President of ''Asociación Dominicana de la Industria del Cigarrillo'' (ASOCIGAR).<ref>{{cite news|title=ASOCIGAR pide al Ministerio Público erradicar el contrabando de cigarros|url=http://cdn.com.do/noticias/2014/09/22/asocigar-pide-al-ministerio-publico-erradicar-el-contrabando-de-cigarros/|accessdate=23 September 2014|agency=NCDN|date=22 September 2014|location=Santo Domingo|language=Spanish}}</ref>
== Early life == Marcos Bisonó was born in [[Santo Domingo]], and is the son of [[architect]] Victor Bisonó Pichardo, born into a prominent family{{#tag:ref|The Bisonó family descends from Jean Bissonnet ({{Abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1817), his wife Marie Framingdano, and their child, Pierre Bissonnet (born in France in 1775). Pierre married twice, first to Marie-Joséphine Sanout and later to Marie Thami. The Bissonnet were landowners in [[Gonaïves]], [[Saint-Domingue]] (currently Haiti) and had to flee amid a [[1804 Haiti Massacre|massacre against whites]] to [[San José de las Matas]], in the then-[[Era de Francia|French-administered Santo Domingo]] (currently the Dominican Republic). Pierre had 1 children with the former: María Josefa (born in Gonaïves, died 1896 in San José de las Matas); with the latter he had 4 children: Pedro Luys (1805-1853), Ana (1806-1886), Miguel (?), Pedro Antonio (1807-1882), all born in San José de las Matas; his father died in 1817, in San José de las Matas. Some children of Miguel and Pedro Luys Bisonó moved from San José de las Matas and established in what today is known as “[[Bisonó|Villa Bisonó]]”, and became wealthy farmers and traders, and eventually a prominent family.<ref name=Bisono-Saturria/>|group=nb}} from [[Villa Bisonó]] in the foothills of the [[Cordillera Septentrional|Northern Mountain-Range]] in [[Santiago Province (Dominican Republic)|Santiago Province]],<ref name=Bisono-Saturria>{{cite book |author1=Juan Francisco Bisonó |author2=Haliday Saturria Vargas |title=Genealogía Serrana |date=October 2011 |publisher=Argos |location=Santo Domingo |isbn=978-9945-408-58-4 |pages= 14, 24, 55–56, 60 |edition=1st |url=http://buenalectura.files.wordpress.com/2011/10/genealogc3ada-serrana.pdf|accessdate=23 September 2014 |language=Spanish |format=pdf |chapter=Inmigración Francesa a San José de las Matas: Tercera inmigración a la Sierra}}</ref><ref name=Balaguer-Memorias>{{cite book|last1=Balaguer|first1=Joaquín|authorlink1=Joaquín Balaguer|title=Memorias de un Cortesano de la Era de Trujillo|date=1988|publisher=[[Grupo Corripio|Editora Corripio]]|location=Santo Domingo|isbn=978-8431202361|pages=12, 420 |language=Spanish|quote=“Ya en esa época, sin embargo, la villa contaba con alguna actividad económica, que se manifestaba con la existencia en ella de varios establecimientos comerciales de cierta importancia. Los más sobresalientes pertenecían a un emigrante catalán, Don Ricaldo Canalda... y a Don Elías Bisonó, dueño además de varias fincas dedicadas a la ganadería. Sus casas eran las dos más poderosas y las que atraían mayor clientela de los campos vecinos. Pero junto a ellas se fueron formando otras más modestas, como las de Washington Lithgow... y la de Don Francisquito Bisonó. (...) La aldea nativa empieza a servir de asiento a numerosos establecimientos comerciales que la convierten poco a poco en una pequeña villa de extraordinaria actividad económica, desproporcionada con su tamaño. Entre esos establecimientos figuran el de Don Alberto Asencio, el de Don Miguel Mercado, el de Francisquito Bisonó y el de Don Juan Caridad Bisonó.”}}</ref> and [[Ivonne Haza]], a renowned national [[soprano]] from [[San Pedro de Macorís]]. He completed elemental school at Colegio Santa Teresita and graduated ''[[Cum Laude]]'' as [[Juris Doctor]] from the [[Universidad Iberoamericana (UNIBE)|Universidad Iberoamericana]]’s Law School. He also completed some courses at the Lawyers Yale School of Management.
Bisonó is descended from [[Domingo Daniel Pichardo]], [[Vice President of the Dominican Republic]] from 1857 to 1858, and [[Fernando Valerio]], who is considered a hero of the [[Battle of Santiago (1844)]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Espinal Hernández|first1=Edwin|title=Dilucidaciones histórico-genealógicas sobre Fernando Valerio|url=http://www.idg.org.do/charlas/1995/abril.pdf|publisher=Instituto Dominicano de Genealogía|accessdate=23 September 2014|language=Spanish|date=April 1995}}</ref>
=== Ancestors=== {{ahnentafel |collapsed=yes |align=center |boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc; |boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9; |boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc; |boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc; |boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe; | 1= 1. '''Marcos Rodolfo Bisonó Haza''' ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1965) | 2= 2. Víctor Gustavo Bisonó Pichardo ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1933, {{Abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1961) | 3= 3. [[Ivonne Haza|Sara María Ivonne Haza del Castillo]] ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1938, {{Abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1961) | 4= 4. Gustavo Nery Bisonó Fernández ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1899, {{Abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1949) | 5= 5. Rosa Pichardo Corona ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1908, {{Abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1931, {{Abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1983) | 6= 6. Luis Felipe Haza González | 7= 7. Rita Indiana del Castillo y Rodríguez-Objío | 8= 8. Juan Caridad Bisonó Checo ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1872, {{Abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1969) | 9= 9. Agapita Fernández Castro |10= 10. Florencio Rodolfo Pichardo Valerio ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1881, {{Abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1907, {{Abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1959) |11= 11. Rosa Corona Collado ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1877, {{Abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1907, {{Abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1964) |12= |13= |14= 14. Luis Temístocles del Castillo García (1854–1922) |15= 15. Dolores Eloísa Rodríguez-Objío Reyes (1867–1941) |16= 16. Joseph Estanislao 'Juan' Bisonó Muñoz ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1840, {{Abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1871, {{Abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1900) |17= 17. María Caridad Checo Rodríguez ({{Abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1871) |18= Juan Fernández |19= |20= 20. Rodolfo Ramón Pichardo Román ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1847, {{Abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1870, {{Abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1927; son of [[Domingo Daniel Pichardo]]) |21= 21. Juana Francisca Valerio Suriel ({{Abbr|b.|born}}&nbsp;1853, {{Abbr|m.|married}}&nbsp;1870, {{Abbr|d.|died}}&nbsp;1944; daughter of [[Fernando Valerio]]) |22= 22. Ramón Corona |23= 23. María Collado |24= |25= |26= |27= |28= 28. Benigno (Ruiz) del Castillo |29= 29. Gabina García Perdomo |30= 30. [[Manuel Rodríguez Objío]] |31= 31. Rita Altagracia Reyes García }}
